Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: My intuition stems from the growing concern about fairness and generalization in neural language models, particularly regarding underrepresented or minority group names—such as names from non-Western cultures, Indigenous communities, or gender-diverse individuals. Existing methods for detecting overfitting often rely on performance metrics like accuracy or loss on validation sets, which can mask poor generalization on rare instances due to dataset imbalance. The references provided highlight powerful representational similarity techniques—RSA in neuroscience-inspired analysis (Paper 2), Tree Kernels for symbolic alignment (Paper 1), and data similarity measures for transfer learning (Paper 3)—but none directly address *structural representational degradation* for sensitive subpopulations across model layers. I propose a novel diagnostic framework that combines intra-layer self-similarity (measuring redundancy within a layer’s representations of rare names) with inter-layer linear Centered Kernel Alignment (CKA) similarity (assessing how consistently these representations evolve across depth). This dual-axis analysis allows us to detect when a model memorizes rather than generalizes rare names—not just through behavioral outputs but via internal representational anomalies. Crucially, this approach shifts focus from aggregate model behavior to subgroup-specific representational fidelity, enabling early detection of overfitting without requiring additional labeled data or probes. Unlike probing classifiers—which may themselves overfit or introduce confounding variables—our method operates directly on activation geometry, aligning with RSA principles while extending them to fairness-aware representation analysis. Furthermore, by focusing on name subgroups stratified by cultural origin, phonotactic rarity, or demographic sensitivity, we introduce a socially grounded dimension to representational similarity analysis not present in prior work.

