  "Idea": "This research introduces 'Learned Representational Integrity Networks' (LRIN), a novel framework that replaces hand-crafted similarity metrics with a contrastively trained diagnostic network to detect overfitting in neural language model representations of rare and minority group names. While prior work uses fixed measures like linear CKA or cosine similarity to assess representational stability, these often lack sensitivity to subtle distortions caused by data imbalance and cultural bias. LRIN addresses this by training a parameterized similarity module—using contrastive learning—to distinguish between healthy, generalized representations and fragmented, overfitted ones. Specifically, we construct positive pairs from semantically coherent name embeddings (e.g., same cultural origin, high frequency in balanced corpora) and negative pairs from rare names exhibiting high activation variance or membership leakage. The LRIN module jointly analyzes intra-layer self-similarity patterns and inter-layer transformation smoothness by processing layer-wise embedding trajectories, learning to identify signatures of memorization such as erratic similarity jumps or divergent clustering. To enhance cultural awareness, we incorporate weak symbolic supervision using phonological features (e.g., IPA transcriptions), morphological regularity scores, and ethnolinguistic kinship trees as auxiliary constraints during training. This hybrid neuro-symbolic design ensures the diagnostic tool remains interpretable and sensitive to linguistically meaningful variation. We evaluate LRIN on BERT-family models pretrained on imbalanced corpora, showing that it outperforms traditional CKA+self-similarity baselines in predicting membership inference attack success, train-test divergence, and downstream fairness degradation for minority names. Crucially, LRIN provides not just a score but actionable insights—highlighting specific layers and name clusters where interventions (e.g., data augm